<body>

<h1>@HI{{iru}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @N{{}}@HI{{ga}} @EM{{@HI{{iru}}}}
<li> @N1{{location}} @HI{{ni}} @N2{{}} @HI{{ga}} @EM{{@HI{{iru}}}}
<li> @N1{{}} @HI{{ha}} @N2{{location}} @HI{{ni}} @EM{{@HI{{iru}}}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{iru}}}} is used when discussing living animate things; <a href="grammar-aru.html">@HI{{aru}}</a>
is used for plants and inanimate objects.
</p>

<p>
In the first sentence pattern the existence or presence of someone or something is stated.
The thing that exists is marked with @HI{{ga}}.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{male}}no@KJ{{person}}ga<strong>imasu</atrong>.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      There is a man.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<hrule>
</p>

<p>
In the second sentence pattern, a location is presented and @EM{{@HI{{iru}}}}
focuses on what exists. @HI{{ni}} may be dropped.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{matter^task^place}}ni@KT{{mira-}}sanga@EM{{imasu}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Mr. Miller is in the office.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<hrule>
</p>

<p>
In the third sentence pattern, a thing is presented as the topic and @EM{{@HI{{iru}}}}
focuses on where that thing is.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{mira-}}sanha@KJ{{matter^task^place}}ni@EM{{imasu}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Mr. Miller is in the office.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<hrule>
</p>

<p>
Note that @EM{{@HI{{iru}}}} uses @HI{{ga}} to mark its object and not @HI{{wo}}.
</p>

